{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477842"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:06:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:06:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14879"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14879"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.16,0.07,0.66,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7570"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60368"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7570"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14879"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45790"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3748"},{"type":"tags","id":"6625"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9278"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18511"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60368"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parent for routine follow-up. She has been experiencing intermittent fatigue and appears pale. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her parent mentions that several family members have had their spleens removed. Her immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 105/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She has pale conjunctivae and mild scleral icterus. Her spleen is palpable 3 cm below the costal margin. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 95 g/L (115-145)\u003Cbr /\u003EMean corpuscular volume 82 fL (77-95)\u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count 8.5 x 10^9/L (4.5-13.5)\u003Cbr /\u003EPlatelet count 250 x 10^9/L (150-450)\u003Cbr /\u003EReticulocyte count 8% (0.5-2.5)\u003Cbr /\u003ETotal bilirubin 35 \u03bcmol/L (3-20)\u003Cbr /\u003EDirect bilirubin 5 \u03bcmol/L (0-7)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency","Sickle cell anaemia","Beta thalassaemia","Hereditary spherocytosis","Iron deficiency anaemia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of chronic haemolysis including anaemia, jaundice, and splenomegaly. The family history of splenectomy is particularly significant. \u003Cstrong\u003EHereditary spherocytosis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given these findings, along with evidence of haemolysis (elevated reticulocyte count and unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia). It is an inherited red cell membrane disorder that typically presents in childhood with anaemia, jaundice, and splenomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta thalassaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can present with similar features, but typically shows microcytosis (low MCV) which is not present here. Additionally, the family history of splenectomy is more suggestive of hereditary spherocytosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute haemolytic episodes triggered by oxidative stress (certain medications, infections, or fava beans) rather than chronic haemolysis. Between episodes, patients are usually asymptomatic with normal blood counts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron deficiency anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E would not explain the elevated reticulocyte count, splenomegaly, or hyperbilirubinaemia. Additionally, the MCV is normal in this case, whereas iron deficiency typically causes microcytosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESickle cell anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents earlier in life with painful crises and would be unlikely in a patient first presenting at age six with mild symptoms. The absence of pain crises in the history makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of hereditary spherocytosis can be confirmed with specialised tests including osmotic fragility testing, eosin-5-maleimide (EMA) binding, or genetic testing. Management may eventually include splenectomy, which explains the family history, but this is typically delayed until after age six years to reduce the risk of post-splenectomy sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spherocytosis is characterized by osmotically fragile red blood cells leading to chronic haemolysis and splenomegaly.","Family history is important in diagnosing hereditary spherocytosis as it follows autosomal dominant inheritance in 75% of cases.","The combination of anaemia, jaundice, and splenomegaly should prompt consideration of hereditary spherocytosis in children."],"references":["Ciepiela O. Old and new insights into the diagnosis of hereditary spherocytosis. Ann Transl Med 2018;6(17):339"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45790"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14879"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","i